Great — Memory is the next major LangChain concept, and it’s extremely important because:

	•	Memory is the heart of chatbots

	•	Memory is crucial for multi-turn agents

	•	Memory is required for underwriting assistants, workflow assistants, PDF assistants, etc.

By the end of this section, you’ll fully understand what memory is, why we need it, why LLMs have no memory by default, and how LangChain implements different types of memory.

And of course — we’ll build a real working code project.

⸻

🟦 1) What is Memory? (Simplest Explanation)

LLMs are stateless.

Meaning:

👉 Every time you ask a question, the model forgets the previous conversation

👉 It only uses the messages you pass to it in the current API call

Example:

You: “My name is Musaddik.”

You: “What is my name?”

Without memory, the LLM won’t know unless you send the whole conversation again.

So Memory = Storing past messages and sending them with each request.

⸻

🟦 2) Why do we need Memory?

Without memory:

	•	Chatbots become “dumb”

	•	Agents forget previous steps

	•	Multi-turn workflows cannot continue

	•	Underwriting logic breaks (“Applicant age? Insurance amount?”)

	•	Human-in-the-loop is impossible

Memory turns a one-shot LLM into a conversational agent.

⸻

🟦 3) Types of Memory in LangChain

LangChain has MANY memory types:

✔ 1. BufferMemory

Stores conversation history as plain text.

Simple, works well for small chats.

✔ 2. ConversationBufferWindowMemory

Stores only last N messages.

✔ 3. ConversationEntityMemory

Extracts entities (name, age, company, etc.) and stores them.

✔ 4. VectorStoreRetrieverMemory

Memorizes things by storing them in a vector store — good for long sessions.

✔ 5. Custom memory

You write your own memory logic.

⸻

🟦 4) How Memory actually works

Memory = A “step” that:

	•	Receives input message

	•	Updates the stored history

	•	Sends history + new message to the LLM

Technically:

User message → Memory → Prompt → LLM → Reply → Memory updates


